  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(25) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Let him down by the wall in a basket.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The basket is the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "spuris",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 15:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where see Note. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Corinthians 11:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " St. Paul describes it by another word (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sarganè",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "which gives the idea of a wicker or rope-work hamper. It seems to follow, from the tone in which the Apostle there speaks of this adventure, that it had been made matter of ridicule. It is connected in his thoughts with the “infirmities” (probably with his smallness of stature) of which he was content to boast. The escape was effected, like that of the spies from the house of Rahab (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and of David from his own house (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 19:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), through an opening or “window” in the town wall. Such a window is still shown in the wall of Damascus as the traditional scene of the escape.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
